Republic strategy for resistance to re-election of Obama
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat counterfeiting in the elections.
At the Brennan Centre, however, the latter is considered a myth, claiming that counterfeiting in elections in the United States is less frequent than lightning deaths.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of elective counterfeiting in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have adopted laws since 2009 that complicate the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon was re-emerged after the November 2010 elections, which brought 675 new seats to the republicans in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the right to vote in 41 states were adopted in one year.
The new electoral laws require the electorate to present a photo identification and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to vote on the day of the vote and deprive citizens of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state had obliged voters to present a photo identification.
Indiana became the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indian law.
The Republican authorities have rushed to extend this practice to other states.
During the last two years, they have initiated legislation that obliges voters to present identity cards with photographs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have the same universal identity card as a medical insurance card.
In fact, 11 per cent of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people who have reached the age required to vote, do not have an identity card with a photograph issued by their state government authority.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds $100.
New restrictions affect young people, minorities and low-income people disproportionately.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required identity card with the photograph.
But that's not all.
Student voters who are believed to vote for democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use a photo identification card issued by their educational institution.
However, these states permit members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use the certificates issued by these clubs for voting.
Until 2004, no state required proof of American nationality for voting.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at restricting the voting of Latin American nationals.
Two thirds of Latin American voters are believed to vote in favour of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators initiated laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on the day of the vote in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those wishing to register.
This limitation has not gone without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to list some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a 17 per cent drop in the registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, republican legislators have enacted laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
Thus, during the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33 per cent of voters who voted early were African-Americans, although the latter were only 13 per cent of the total number of voters in the state.
The same was true of Latin American citizens.
Only 11 per cent of the voters represented 24 per cent of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, which, by forming 76 per cent of voters, were only 46 per cent of voters in the short term.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters actively oppose the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws were promised by democratic governors.
The effects of the most ambiguous laws were suspended when the United States Attorney General intervened.
This has partially limited the negative effects.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the identification of a photograph.
Nevertheless, the new rules that had entered into force would certainly make it difficult to exercise electoral law in the 2012 elections.
Critics of Democrats condemn the biases of the laws that have been enacted, with a clear focus on influencing the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
The 2011 report of the Centre of Brennan shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed by the electorate to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the appearance of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
