Higgs Boson in detail
Last summer, reports that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused a real exaggeration, not without justification.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, not much.
In addition, this is the last particle that was predicted to exist in the Standard Model - our best, or, in any case, “the least imperfect” description of nature and the behavior of matter - but which was previously not found in an experimental way.
But physicists aren't quite sure it's the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it is very much like the Higgs boson foretold in the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data are not yet available for full confidence.
Let's imagine what the Higgs boson is, because the chances of being wrong seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is one law in this world that is completely inevitable, stating that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to get past this rule, not even try too hard, or hurt yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it also turns out that there is one law of a similar nature: the principle of Paula's exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same “quant state” is “state” in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Hence, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good-natured citizens called farmes, who wisely obey Paula's principle.
In another, there are bosons, a loathsome gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything — at least that principle — that means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (in fact, quite unusual) the article Adventure Laboratory Berkeley, these bosons are divided into two groups: the ones we're not going to talk about here, and the “particles of force” that are the main forces of nature, and some of them are Higgs bosons.
These very bosons should be emphasized, not all of them are exotic beings, as you might think.
In fact, if you're able to read this chronicle, it's because of one incredibly banal boson: photon, or "part of the light", which is the "courier" of electromagnetic power.
In fact, when one particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it breaks the electromagnetic field in this particular place, like a stone thrown into a spring.
This “disruption” gives birth to an electromagnetic wave (world, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon, and therefore one of the bosons of the “power carrier”.
A more stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the difference that the boson must have been “broken” by another field, the Higgs field.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable in the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very and very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That is why a huge particle accelerator is needed, such as the one used in the CERN, the Great Adrienne Collider, which is a 27-km ring! - to achieve such enormous energy.
The similarity with the electromagnetic field is also useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs Boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, and others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never hold on to a refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have a mass, while others (such as photon, by the way) do not have one.
So, what can all these studies bring, Mrs. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to distinguish between observations and projections of the MM.
In addition, some of them are passionate about finding such a difference, since the slightest discrepancy can open the door for “new physics” and shut some of the gaps in the Model.
The latter, to be said, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter that forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
But until such time, such differences were found in the CERN.
Consequences
It would be more difficult to predict the benefits of these studies for the average person's daily life, but it would be a mistake to assume that he is not.
See, at the beginning of the 1960 ’ s, pioneers in laser research at Bell’s laboratories could not even guess what revolution their work would be like.
They predicted their applications in science, but no more.
In fact, already a late physicist, Willard Boyle, who worked at the Bell Labs, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (formerly impulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was initially considered as a “laboratory gadget”.
Imagine...
In addition, the annex can be found for tools accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his research in 1969.
This sensor, although not its original purpose, is now an eye for all digital cameras in the world and has earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This does not mean, of course, that the work of the Great Adront Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it just shows that everything can happen.
