The total opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks numbered transactions between receiving parties with commission fees for processing them.
Moreover, as often happens to these technologies, it is clear that a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, an invented Satoshi Nakamoto (alias), is simultaneously a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euros ...) and a secure BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows the exchange of files between participants at the same level.
Some 200,000 operations have already been registered with 15,000 computers online.
Several thousand sites accept battle stations for donations or as a means of payment.
At a maximum of 30 Euros (23 Euros) in June 2011, five months later, the bitcoincharts.com had dropped to $2 before returning today to about ten dollars.
Nothing special compared to the world exchange of real money or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, was interested in the system.
He describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competiting with a dollar or a euro” and “like ordinary currencies”.
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as credits used to advance video games that are earned in the game process or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The Facebook social network has also developed such a system.
But exchange operations always control and process a central body.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are held simultaneously by accountants, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually occurs between two e-mails, like e-mails.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
