Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as a second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated actively in several Agency projects over the years.
But the way to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always understood.
Recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, which on 6 December 1933 presented an idea in the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory from his innovative work “Introduction into Space Science”.
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after a few years Sterfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won Robert Esno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch's Prize for Space Introduction.
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great advocate of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned space propagandist, and his contribution was assessed by the fact that one of the craters on the other side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway train equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the project.
It is not even clear that a rocket had to be used to launch or brake the trolley.
The information on this cloth is only known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has begun to contemplate missiles.
The study was carried out by the Arms Technology Section in cooperation with Professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzicki.
The remaining materials show that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the specialized press developed the idea of a photoelectric fighter missile proposed by the Rogozinski engineer, and the following year came the work of the Air Torpedo Missile and Air Missile Bomb by the author of Leliva-Kjioblocki.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Prior to the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee) coordinated all work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its work, the beginning of the war ended.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polish Society of Astronautics).
For the first time, society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine “Problems”, which publishes four voluminous articles on astronomy.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovic suggested that a society should be organized for space.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already in circulation, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautics Society (POA) has tried to join the International Astronautics Federation (based in 1951) and has already become a member in the autumn of the POA.
The following year, the first President of the PLA Kazimež Zarankević (1902-1959) became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, POA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological missile RM (Meteorological Missile), which has become the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first was launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, capable of overcoming the distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
An improved version of RM-1A was subsequently built and tests of a two-stage RM-2 rocket were conducted in the Bled Desert in the summer of 1959.
The rocket was about 1.4 metres long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work, the RM-34 rocket could have traveled 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
But further development was suspended in 1962.
The first RM rockets were succeeded by the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (designed as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B 0.34 litres, and Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed a Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket, with a starting weight of 380 kg, was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg at a height of approximately 60 km.
The versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland ' s accession to COSPAR (the Space Research Committee) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, under the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
