Sabo: "Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, the US-Europe liaison expert, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic road.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Germany must now be careful about its special relations with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that the American position is not supported either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, from a policy that the United States was governed by to its own German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the lack of a coherent common policy for Europeans.
Thus, the Germans are once again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that as long as they only perceive their role, they are on their way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
The foreign policy pursued by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It is a willingness to take a national position independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policies, i.e. exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ significantly from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf States.
It therefore needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elite in Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to that, it's not entirely a unilateral connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in German calculations.
Did Germany harm its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I'm sure that in Europe and even in the United States, the understanding of the German position prevails.
That's why I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
There are divergent views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, the veto was clearly advocated.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government has sufficient understanding of the European position at heart.
But with regard to the local political situation, the Government certainly cannot take that position openly.
I believe that substantial differences of opinion are not as significant as always.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all thrilled with Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would have been a little easier for the Germans if there was a single, undisputed European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are forced to act instead on the basis of their own vision.
That's exactly what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position in the future.
It is clear that it is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
It's always been a touchy topic.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take the lead?
Or is Germany still playing a leading role?
Germany has not yet gotten used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes an important role, there are a variety of anti-German feelings.
The Germans are not just dealing with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It should take into account a wide range of neighbours and views, which is not easy.
So the U.S. influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who's left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, it's a life that makes you feel uncomfortable or hateful.
Stephen Sabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., where academics and political experts from Europe and North America are working together on the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo, a member of the German Marshall Foundation, specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
