Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations of poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning's presence in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence requires that the case be closed on the grounds that the conditions of Manning ' s detention were cruel.
The U.S. Private Army is accused of kidnapping several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, charged with the largest diversion of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment that he said he had to endure while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, stated that the weekly visits to Manning by prison officials within nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the Manning motion for a stay on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and were in itself sufficient punishment was conducted the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of kidnapping several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks didn't confirm that it was Manning that was the source of the information.
During Friday's hearing, Prosecutor Feyn and Manning reviewed the reports that had been completed since Manning's visits to the administration during his stay at Quantico prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he viewed the treatment of the prison administration as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized”.
The reports under review do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manninga was directly questioned about his conditions of detention, Feyn claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed his oral concern about these issues and that his visiting representatives of the Administration had discussed these problems with him and had stated that they would be concerned but not recorded in writing.
"They wrote down "no problems" (after discussion of my complaints), but that does not mean that I did not raise the subject in a conversation," says Manning.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Linde, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a meeting of the commission dealing with the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted to ensure that he was removed from the regime “warning traumatism” and reduced conditions of detention.
The representatives of the military leadership explained that a limited regime of detention - to a level below the suicide-prevention surveillance regime - had been introduced to protect the prisoner and to protect others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I was okay with them to lift the trauma prevention regime... so that my standard of living would improve, in my opinion," explained Manning.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait and that he had once lost consciousness because of intense heat.
He explained that it is psychologically difficult when you are not allowed to know how your participation is resolved and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world was flocking to Camp Arrigan's base, to the size of my prison," Manning said Thursday.
- I thought I was going to die in that cage."
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often even more than 23 hours a day — alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only mattresses, blankets, slippers, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says that he tried to move because sleeping or even lying there during the day prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly struck by a light that penetrated the camera outside.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned into bed at night, he was said to have been awakened and forced to turn around.
Counsel Manning filed an official objection to the ill-treatment of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
Furthermore, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about a statement he had made during his testimony Thursday that, after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners in the morning.
Manning stated that he had not been able to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to questions from the judge on Friday, Manning said that he had understood from the order of the guard that he should leave the blanket to which he could hide, but admitted that no one had specifically ordered him to leave.
On Thursday, Manning stated that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told the officer that he could use a rubber vest or a shoelace to traumatize himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning's certificate, his underwear, his hookers, and his glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had to experience during his detention and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning was found guilty by a military court that should begin his case early next year.
The defence stated that it planned to invite Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and to challenge other charges as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, the prosecution is expected to insist that conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of detainees with maximum severity.
Among the charges brought to Manning are aid to the enemy, illegal promotion of Internet disclosure, transmission of information relating to national defence, and abduction of State property or documents.
If he is convicted of all points of the indictment, he may face life imprisonment.
My national self-determination crisis is the story of an American of Mexican origin.
