Old battles in the new Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas group could become a fragile foundation for the future peace
Is long - term peace between Arabs and Israelis possible in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed has led to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
They sound familiar, pointless disputes about who started the first one; many buildings have been destroyed; over 140 Palestinians have been killed, most of them civilians, and six Israelis; and for the first time during the conflict, rockets launched from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, while the Israelites and the Palestinians were hopelessly linked to their eternal conflict, changes had come to the Middle East.
This can be seen in different ways, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have circled many persistent realities in the rebel storm, and Palestinians with the Israelis have not been able to stay away from the storm that struck the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope that this deadly stalemate will come to an end.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation did not give rise to optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on 21 November, was to be implemented, the clashes that took place this week only strengthened the positions of the forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamic Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, said they had forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they had suffered.
Although some of the leaders of the group have been destroyed and 1.7 million have been blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has not been able to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank of the Jordan River, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fath movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grew, Hamas developed new influential and rich friends.
The resurgent regional leader of Turkey, who had once been Israel's closest ally among the Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed the example of Qatar, one of the richest and dynamic developing States of the Persian Gulf.
Hamas champions claim the establishment of the Islamic Crescent around Israel, from Lebanon to the north, in which the Hezbollah paramilitary group is ruling, to Syria, where more and more Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad's power, and further to Jordan, where the king's authorities are threatening Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region took place on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, in Egypt, where President Mohammed Mursey strengthened the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid no attention to Hamas ' support.
On the contrary, Muslim brothers are an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic locations, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice could not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was laid down.
The Israeli Iron Dome missile system has justified the cost of its creation and has successfully destroyed many of Hamas' rockets.
Israelis can sleep peacefully for at least some time.
With regard to diplomacy, the United States remained faithful to its unwavering position; many European countries also blamed the beginning of the last round of violence against Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially in the Government of Binyamina Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has been able to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, partly through a wall that enters the West Bank of the Jordan River, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from the point of view of international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party, as part of preparations for the 22 January elections, has joined with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very comfortable.
What is the point of perpetuating the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they put all the power into their hands in the West Bank, would they not start launching rockets from there towards Israel, as their gatherings in the Gaza Strip do?
It's better to keep them behind the wall, and tighten any attempts to lift their heads.
The supporters of the hard line may win; however, their calculations may be overturned in the Arab spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries have not the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defence part of Israel's budget is greater than all its Arab neighbours combined.
The opening of a war with the regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments to strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of the President of Egypt, Mursey, who worked with Barack Obama on the ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel must take into account the long-term implications of its policies.
As democratic changes occur in the Arab countries, the Palestinian denial of the right to self-determination is a slow-action bomb that will sooner or later explode in the occupied territories of Israel, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression has already undermined the foundations of democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic dimension of the growth of the Arab population only exacerbates these problems.
For bloodbath operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement, the growing discontent of the international community has to be paid.
Both sides need an external impulse
The only solution that has been repeatedly called upon by healthy representatives from both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world, and our newspaper: the formation of two States and Israeli concessions in exchange for security.
The hope remains not too impressive in the short term - the hope that the ceasefire will enable other countries to have a more effective impact on the sides of the conflict.
Egypt, which is long overdue in its decision to stop arms transfers to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, is more useful than ever to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish State adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fath movements.
This would have done more to create a Palestinian State than the forthcoming vote in the United Nations, which could result in recognition of the virtual state of Palestine.
President Obama must also play a role in placing Israel at the negotiating table.
During his first term, he had never presented his own plan for a peaceful settlement.
Upon returning to the White House, he continued to show that he was unwilling to join the problem.
It's a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
