The warnings of the harm of smoking and images of parts of the body affected by disease are contrasted with those of weary green boxes identical to cigarettes for all brands.
In world practice, Australia ' s uniform packaging law on cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing logos and color-coded stamps with the same yellow and olive-coloured box with horrendous pictures of children affected by the disease of parts of the body and images of children whose health is undermined by their parents ' smoking.
In addition to the various pictures and inscriptions that warn of the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packages introduced on this Saturday is the names of the stamps that are printed in the same small font.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the packaging of tobacco products.
The Federal Government of Australia declares that the aim of this measure is to prevent young people from smoking, depriving them of this harmful habit of fashion status.
Such a decision was based on studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 were, in 99 cases, never becoming smokers.
“It is obvious that even at a young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies try to make through packaging,” explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the world ' s smallest proportions of smokers, so these changes will not have a particular impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
