I used to think, like many, that boredom was an invention about recent times when people had more free time.
This is not the case, claims Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary of Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact boredom can boast of a very ancient history," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii, Latin inscriptions of boredom dating back to the first century were found.
The question of how we understand boredom remains open.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, associate professor at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, that understanding and vision of boredom often changed.
Having studied the research materials on this subject and asked a question to the task force of 100, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people “want but cannot do what pleases them”.
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a boring person doesn't do something he wants to do.
There's nothing you want to do with apathy.
The main thing in the long run, he said, was “a disturbance in attention and the resulting deterioration in mood and the feeling that time is moving slowly”.
According to the description of boredom, it may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood claims that despite the possible connection between these conditions, people who miss the causes of problems in the world and the circumstances, and people who experience depression, see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel like we're bored when it's just really hard to focus on something.
In his study “Unoccupied Reason: Defining Boring for Attention,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment that participants listened to the recording of a vote reading the journal.
Some participants also heard loud sounds outside the area of the television programme included in the next room, others heard the same sounds at low noise, so they could hardly be analyzed, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without a foreign soundtrack.
Those who heard low - volume TV said that they were bored, more often than not, they found it difficult to concentrate, but they did not know the reason and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, the distraction may be boring, says Mark J. Fenské, Associate Professor of Neurology at the University of Gwelf, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, “for example, looking at the flow of goods on the conveyor belt in search of marriage, distracting music can help to avoid boredom.”
It is believed that it continues that when people start climbing on a chair or drawing caracoli on a sheet of paper, they do it for boredom, but now we know that such actions just help not to relax physically.
“The study has shown that children who are not banned from climbing and turning learn better and remember more information than children from whom they are asked to sit modestly,” says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we're all bored with the delay of the flight (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting film.
However, different people demonstrate a different degree of boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a special “steel of boredom” to measure such individual characteristics.
Questions and allegations, such as “Many of what I have to do, uniformly and monotonously” or “I am too interested, so there is no time for anything”.
With the help of such questionnaires, researchers have determined that boys miss girls more often, says Stephen Vodanovic, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when there are various outside annoyers.
In general, however, adolescents often miss each other.
In 1991, Reed Larson, Professor of Personal and Social Development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he connected with nearly 400 adolescents and their parents 7-8 times a day using a pager.
The results were as follows: 32 per cent of adolescents said they were bored at school and during their homework, and 23 per cent said they were bored outside the school.
